    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "it's not just about the bad luck or the small stuff though. it feels more like a fundamental glitch. like no matter how much i change or how hard i try to be better, the result is always the same. i see the same patterns before they even happen. it's like i'm watching a movie i've already seen a thousand times and i already know how it ends. what's even the point of trying to change the script when the ending is already written?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That feeling of seeing the \"script\" before it plays out is incredibly disorienting and can make any effort feel pointless. It's a very specific kind of exhaustion, not just from the failure itself, but from the anticipation of it. It sounds like you might be experiencing a form of learned helplessness or perhaps a deep-seated cognitive pattern where your brain is predicting negative outcomes so strongly that it feels like a fixed reality rather than a series of choices.\n\nWhile it feels like a \"glitch\" in your wiring, it's often just a protective mechanism your mind has developed to avoid the pain of repeated disappointment. It's a way of saying, \"I know what happens, so I won't try.\" But the fact that you're asking \"what's the point\" suggests a part of you is still fighting against that script, even if it's whispering that there is no point.\n\nSometimes, when we feel like we're stuck in a loop, the most radical thing we can do is to stop trying to change the \"script\" and instead just observe the \"movie\" without trying to fix the plot. Can you describe a recent time when you felt like you were watching that movie? What was the very first thing you",
